    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/11",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">Mandelbrot developed an early interest in the stochastic modeling of financial markets. Familiar with the work of Louis Bachelier (<i>see</i> <b>Bachelier, Louis</b> <b>(1870â€“1946)</b>), Mandelbrot published a series of pioneering studies [6â€“8, 21] on the tail behavior of the distribution of price variations, where he advocated the use of heavy-tailed distributions and scale-invariant Levy processes for modeling price Â´ fluctuations. The discovery of the heavy-tailed nature of price movements led him to coin the term \"wild randomness\" for describing market behavior, as opposed to the \"mild randomness\" represented by Bachelier's Brownian model, which later became the standard approach embodied in the Blackâ€“Scholes model. Mandelbrot likened the sudden bursts of volatility in financial markets to the \"Noah effect\", by analogy with the flood which destroys the world in Noah's biblical story:</p>",
      "page": 284,
      "polygon": [
        [
          303.1199951171875,
          412.92755126953125
        ],
        [
          515.3984375,
          412.92755126953125
