    {
      "id": "/page/1/Text/4",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">The market's second wild traitâ€”almost cyclesâ€”is prefigured in the story of Joseph. The Pharaoh dreamed that seven fat cattle were feeding in the meadows, when seven lean kine rose out of the Nile and ate them. [<i>...</i>] Joseph, a Hebrew slave, called the dreams prophetic : Seven years of famine would follow seven years of prosperity. [<i>...</i>] Of course, this is not a regular or predictable pattern. But the appearance of one is strong. Behind it is the influence of long-range dependence in an otherwise random process or, put another way, a long-term memory through which the past continues to influence the random fluctuations of the present. I called these two distinct forms of wild behavior the Noah effect and the Joseph effect. They are two aspects of one reality.</p>",
      "page": 369,
      "polygon": [
        [
          91.271484375,
          250.6678466796875
        ],
        [
          281.2578125,
          250.6678466796875
        ],
        [
